The Dataset¶

In this machine learning project, I will be attempting to predict the future prices of the Google stock price using its historical data. The dataset I will be using contains information on Google stock price from August 18, 2004 to September 20, 2021. Each row in this dataset contains a daily record of the price of one share of a Google stock.

The columns of the dataset are:

  • Date -- The date of the record.
  • Open -- The opening price of the day (when trading starts).
  • High -- The highest trade price during the day.
  • Low -- The lowest trade price during the day.
  • Close -- The closing price for the day (when trading is finished).
  • Volume -- The number of shares traded.
  • Adj Close -- The daily closing price, adjusted retroactively to include any corporate actions.

Creating Predictor Variables¶

For this machine learning model, I will be using the following variables as potential predictors:

  • The average price from the past 5 days.
  • The average price from the past 30 days.
  • The average price from the past 100 days.
  • The standard deviation of the price over the past 5 days.
  • The standard deviation of the price over the past 30 days.
  • The standard deviation of the price over the past 100 days.

The reason for using past data for my predictors variables is because of the nature of stock market data. Stock market data is sequential, meaning that each row comes a day after the previous row. Because of this, we have to be careful not to inject any 'future' knowledge in our model. Including any current prices in our model will make our model look good, but it will make it unrealistic since we can never know the stock price upfront. As a result, we can only use prices from the past as part of our predictor variables.

In [8]:
#add predictor variables to the dataset
def compute_avg_price_ndays(df, num_days):
    col_name = 'AVG Price ' + str(num_days) + ' days'
    for index, row in df.iterrows():
        start_index = index - num_days
        if start_index not in df.index:
            df.loc[index, col_name] = np.nan
        else:
            avg_price = df.loc[start_index:(index - 1), 'Close'].mean()
            #stock prices should only have two decimal places
            rounded_avg_price = round(avg_price, 2)
            df.loc[index, col_name] = rounded_avg_price

def compute_std_price_ndays(df, num_days):
    col_name = 'STD Price ' + str(num_days) + ' days'
    for index, row in df.iterrows():
        start_index = index - num_days
        if start_index not in df.index:
            df.loc[index, col_name] = np.nan
        else:
            std_price = df.loc[start_index:(index - 1), 'Close'].std()
            df.loc[index, col_name] = std_price

Train and Test Splits¶

Now it's time to split our data into a train dataset and a test dataset. But before we can do that, we should remove any rows that contain NaN values. Since we have a column that computes the average price from the past 100 days, the first 100 rows of our dataset will have NaN values in that column.

In [11]:
#remove the rows with NaN values
stocks.dropna(inplace=True, axis=0)
stocks.isnull().sum()

There are many different ratios we can use to split our train and test set. For this project, we will just assign 80 percent of our data to our train set and the other 20 percent to our test set. Normally we would randomize which rows go into the train set, but since our dataset has a time series nature, our train set will consist of the first 80 percent of the rows.

Making Predictions¶

Using the new predictor variables we created, let's instantiate our model and train it over the train set, and then have the computer try and predict the stock prices over the test set. For now, we will just include all six of our variables in our linear regression model.

In [14]:
#extract the predictor columns
predictors = []
for col in stocks.columns:
    if col.startswith('AVG') or col.startswith('STD'):
        predictors.append(col)
print('predictors variables: ' + str(predictors))

#create regression model
lr = LinearRegression()
lr.fit(train_stocks[predictors], train_stocks['Close'])
predictions = lr.predict(test_stocks[predictors])
mse = mean_squared_error(test_stocks['Close'], predictions)
rmse = mse**0.5
mae = mean_absolute_error(test_stocks['Close'], predictions)
print('rmse: ' + str(rmse), '\nmae: ' + str(mae))

Throughout the rest of this project we will only focus on the mean absolute error since it is more intuitive than the root mean squared error. Variable Selection¶

Although our predictions above don't look too bad, let's try to improve our model (reduce mae). There are several ways to improve a regression model, but one of the best ways is to do variable selection. In our model above we simply included all six predictors, but let's check and see if any other combinations of our predictors will result in a lower mae.

In [17]:
#create mae calculator
def compute_mae(predictors):
    lr = LinearRegression()
    lr.fit(train_stocks[predictors], train_stocks['Close'])
    predictions = lr.predict(test_stocks[predictors])
    mae = mean_absolute_error(test_stocks['Close'], predictions)
    return mae
In [18]:
mae_dict = {}
predictor_list = []
predictors = []
for col in stocks.columns:
    if col.startswith('AVG') or col.startswith('STD'):
        predictors.append(col)

#compute mae for all possible models        
for i in range(1, len(predictors) + 1):        
    for comb in combinations(predictors, i):
        comb_list = list(comb)
        mae = compute_mae(comb_list)
        mae_dict[tuple(comb_list)] = mae

#sort the mae_dict from lowest to highest mae
sorted_mae_dict = {k: v for k, v in sorted(mae_dict.items(), key=lambda item: item[1])}
#only print the first 10 items
{k: sorted_mae_dict[k] for k in list(sorted_mae_dict)[:10]}

With six different predictor variables, there are a total of 63 possible models (6C1 + 6C2 + ..... + 6C6). Based on the sorted_mae_dict from above, the model that produces the lowest mae has the variables [ 'AVG Price 5 days', 'AVG Price 30 days', 'AVG Price 100 days' ]. We will use this model as our final model.

Best Model¶

In [19]:
best_predictors = ['AVG Price 5 days', 'AVG Price 30 days', 'AVG Price 100 days']

#create regression model
lr = LinearRegression()
lr.fit(train_stocks[best_predictors], train_stocks['Close'])
best_predictions = lr.predict(test_stocks[best_predictors])
mae = mean_absolute_error(test_stocks['Close'], best_predictions)
print('mae: ' + str(mae))

Our linear regression model has the above coefficents and y-intercept. In other words, the predicted stock price for any given day is 1.071 (average price over the past 5 days) - 0.107 (average price over the past 30 days) + 0.038 * (average price over the past 100 days) + 0.125.

Conclusion¶

The final model had a mean absolute error of 25.86. Although the error seems pretty trivial on the graph, this error is way too high for this stock price predicting model to be used in the real world. An mae of 25.86 means that your daily predictions are expected to be off by an average of 25 dollars and 86 cents, which is not ideal if you are trying to make a profit off of stocks. However, our machine learning model was still able to detect the big growths and dips in the prices, and it did a pretty good job of following the overall trend of the Google stock over its lifetime.
